<subSubSection id="C1F06505FFD4017D4DC2F96720E0F8CD" pageId="4" pageNumber="254" type="description">
<paragraph id="8955368EFFD4017D4DC2F96720E0F8CD" blockId="4.[136,1452,1744,1879]" pageId="4" pageNumber="254">
In 2015, the second author visited the region of Napoli and made an excursion to Mount Vesuvius, where he collected a non-flowering rosette which he cultivated in his garden. It came into flower and seeded freely around the garden. When the second author came to Altenberg in 
<date id="FD54104EFFD4017D4F0CF8AE2788F8A8" box="[582,765,1816,1843]" pageId="4" pageNumber="254" value="2019-09">September 2019</date>
and heard that these nice flowering plants (
<figureCitation id="11D12A0BFFD4017D49ADF8AE205FF8A8" box="[1255,1322,1816,1843]" captionStart="FIGURE 2" captionStartId="2.[136,229,1928,1950]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,190,1903]" captionTargetId="figure-19@2.[151,1436,190,1903]" captionTargetPageId="2" captionText="FIGURE 2. Cultivation of Hieracium “garibaldianum” in the garden of G. Brandstätter." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5414532" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5414532/files/figure.png" pageId="4" pageNumber="254">Fig. 2</figureCitation>
) originated from Vesuvius, he immediately recalled the drawing of Fries. Some plants were pressed for further detailed studies.
</paragraph>
